==Current plates==
Geologists generally agree that the following tectonic plates currently exist on the Earth's surface with roughly definable boundaries. Tectonic plates are sometimes subdivided into three fairly arbitrary categories: ''major'' (or ''primary'') ''plates'', ''minor'' (or ''secondary'') ''plates'', and ''microplates'' (or ''tertiary plates'').

===Major/main plates===
These plates comprise the bulk of the continents and the [[Pacific Ocean]]. For purposes of this list, a '''major plate''' is any plate with an area greater than 20 million km<sup>2</sup>.
* {{annotated link|Pacific Plate}} – 103,300,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|North American Plate}} – 75,900,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Eurasian Plate}} –  67,800,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|African Plate}} – 61,300,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Antarctic Plate}} – 60,900,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Indo-Australian Plate}} – 58,900,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> often considered two plates:
** {{annotated link|Australian Plate}} – 47,000,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
** {{annotated link|Indian Plate}} – 11,900,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|South American Plate}} – 43,600,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>

===Minor plates===
These smaller plates are often not shown on major plate maps, as the majority do not comprise significant land area. For purposes of this list, a '''minor plate''' is any plate with an area less than 20 million km<sup>2</sup> but greater than 1 million km<sup>2</sup>.
* {{annotated link|Somali Plate}} – 16,700,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Nazca Plate}} – 15,600,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Philippine Sea Plate}} – 5,500,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Arabian Plate}} – 5,000,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Caribbean Plate}} – 3,300,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Cocos Plate}} – 2,900,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Caroline Plate}} – 1,700,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Scotia Plate}} – 1,600,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|Burma Plate}} – 1,100,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>
* {{annotated link|New Hebrides Plate}} – 1,100,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>

===Microplates===
These plates are often grouped with an adjacent major plate on a major plate map. For purposes of this list, a microplate is any plate with an area less than 1 million km<sup>2</sup>. Some models identify more minor plates within current [[Orogeny|orogens]] (events that lead to a large structural deformation of the Earth's lithosphere) like the Apulian, Explorer, Gorda, and Philippine Mobile Belt plates.  There may be scientific consensus as to whether such plates should be considered distinct portions of the crust; thus new research could change this list.<ref>Tetsuzo Seno, Taro Sakurai, and Seth Stein. 1996. ''Can the Okhotsk plate be discriminated from the North American plate?''  J. Geophys. Res., 101, 11305-11315 ([http://www.eri.u-tokyo.ac.jp/seno/Old/ok_abst.html abstract])</ref><ref>Bird, P. (2003). "An updated digital model of plate boundaries". Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems 4 (3): 1027. {{doi|10.1029/2001GC000252}}. http://peterbird.name/publications/2003_PB2002/2003_PB2002.htm.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Great Rift Valley of Madagascar: An extension of the Africa–Somali diffusive plate boundary?|author1=Timothy M. Kusky |author2=Erkan Toraman |author3=Tsilavo Raharimahefa  |last-author-amp=yes |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1342937X06002711|publisher=International Association for Gondwana Research Published by Elsevier B.V.|date=2006-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=Greenland Survey Bulletin|title=Greenland from Archaean to Quaternary|author1=Niels Henriksen|author2=A.K. Higgins|author3=Feiko Kalsbeek|author4=T. Christopher R. Pulvertaft|url=http://www.geus.dk/publications/bull-gl/nr185/nr185_p12-24.pdf|access-date=2009-10-04|year=2000|issue=185|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207074112/http://www.geus.dk/publications/bull-gl/nr185/nr185_p12-24.pdf|archivedate=2008-12-07|df=}}</ref>
